Imprting Data

Download the files AEMOPriceDataSimple.csv and SydTemp.csv, along with the R script PS1Readin.R (which loads and formats the data). The AEMO ???le contains daily average Regional Reference Price (RRP) for New South Wales (Australia), and is adapted from http://www.aemo.com.au/Electricity/Data. The data gives the daily average spot price over 2013. The SydTemp file gives daily maximum and minimum temperatures at Observatory Hill, Sydney since 1859, and is taken from the main weather observatory http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/data-services/.

Up to 5th degree the p value suggest the coefficients are predictive. The 10th degree model is clearly overfitting the data, couple of points on the tails are driving it. Up to the 5th degree the coefficients seem to have good predictive power and hence I think this 5th degree polinomial is a good model. We have studied about spline models in the last class and hence I would like to investigate if it has any better fit then this current model.

Splines

I am using natural splines which enforces linearity on the tails (this would get rid of overfittign on the small data at the tails).

library("splines")
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
splines3<-lm(RRP_1~ns(minTemp_1,df=3))
plot(minTemp_1,RRP_1)
points(minTemp_1, splines3$fitted, pch='*', col='red')
predpoints<-seq(min(minTemp_1), max(minTemp_1), length.out=300)
lines(predpoints, predict(splines3, data.frame(minTemp_1=predpoints)), col='blue')

splines5<-lm(RRP_1~ns(minTemp_1,df=5))
plot(minTemp_1,RRP_1)
points(minTemp_1, splines5$fitted, pch='*', col='red')
predpoints<-seq(min(minTemp_1), max(minTemp_1), length.out=300)
lines(predpoints, predict(splines5, data.frame(minTemp_1=predpoints)), col='blue')

splines10<-lm(RRP_1~ns(minTemp_1,df=10))
plot(minTemp_1,RRP_1)
points(minTemp_1, splines10$fitted, pch='*', col='red')
predpoints<-seq(min(minTemp_1), max(minTemp_1), length.out=300)
lines(predpoints, predict(splines10, data.frame(minTemp_1=predpoints)), col='blue')

qqnorm(splines5$residuals); qqline(splines5$residuals)

The 10th degree splines is clearly doing a good job at fitting to the datapints but it seems very erratic in the middle of the data which is due to overfitting. In my opinion the splines with 5 degrees of freedom looks like the best fit to the data without having random behaviour at middle or the tails. I will be using this model to predict new values. (df 10 is clearly overfitting)

Summary

I have tried out linear models with min temperature, max temperature and both temperature. The resutls show that min and max are highly correlated hence usign either of them is sufficient. The QQ plot suggested that there might be a nin linear relationship, hence I have investigated polinomial models. The polinomial models did a good job at fitting to the data, however above the 5th degree polinomial there started to be a erratic behavior at the tails, which is due to overfitting. I have aslo tried natural splines models, where I tried up to 10 degrees of freedom. The 5ht degree splines was doing a much more believeble job than the 10, hence I compared it with the previous 5th degree polinomial and the 10 splines model. In conclusion, both 5th degree polinomial and 5 df splines are doing a good job at fitting the data and I chose the 5 df splines as the prediction model as it had a bit nicer tail behaviour (I have done an ANOVA on the models). The day-of-the-week showed a small difference between week and weekends, but I had not enough time to see if this difference is statistically significant.

We have studied about spline models in the last class and hence I would like to investigate if it has any better fit then this current model.

Splines

I am using natural splines which enforces linearity on the tails (this would get rid of overfittign on the small data at the tails).

library("splines")
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
splines3<-lm(RRP_1~ns(minTemp_1,df=3))
plot(minTemp_1,RRP_1)
points(minTemp_1, splines3$fitted, pch='*', col='red')
predpoints<-seq(min(minTemp_1), max(minTemp_1), length.out=300)
lines(predpoints, predict(splines3, data.frame(minTemp_1=predpoints)), col='blue')

splines5<-lm(RRP_1~ns(minTemp_1,df=5))
plot(minTemp_1,RRP_1)
points(minTemp_1, splines5$fitted, pch='*', col='red')
predpoints<-seq(min(minTemp_1), max(minTemp_1), length.out=300)
lines(predpoints, predict(splines5, data.frame(minTemp_1=predpoints)), col='blue')

splines10<-lm(RRP_1~ns(minTemp_1,df=10))
plot(minTemp_1,RRP_1)
points(minTemp_1, splines10$fitted, pch='*', col='red')
predpoints<-seq(min(minTemp_1), max(minTemp_1), length.out=300)
lines(predpoints, predict(splines10, data.frame(minTemp_1=predpoints)), col='blue')

qqnorm(splines5$residuals); qqline(splines5$residuals)

The 10th degree splines is clearly doing a good job at fitting to the datapints but it seems very erratic in the middle of the data which is due to overfitting. In my opinion the splines with 5 degrees of freedom looks like the best fit to the data without having random behaviour at middle or the tails. I will be using this model to predict new values. (df 10 is clearly overfitting)

Summary

I have tried out linear models with min temperature, max temperature and both temperature. The resutls show that min and max are highly correlated hence usign either of them is sufficient. The QQ plot suggested that there might be a nin linear relationship, hence I have investigated polinomial models. The polinomial models did a good job at fitting to the data, however above the 5th degree polinomial there started to be a erratic behavior at the tails, which is due to overfitting. I have aslo tried natural splines models, where I tried up to 10 degrees of freedom. The 5ht degree splines was doing a much more believeble job than the 10, hence I compared it with the previous 5th degree polinomial and the 10 splines model. In conclusion, both 5th degree polinomial and 5 df splines are doing a good job at fitting the data and I chose the 5 df splines as the prediction model as it had a bit nicer tail behaviour (I have done an ANOVA on the models). The day-of-the-week showed a small difference between week and weekends, but I had not enough time to see if this difference is statistically significant.
